*Non-entertainment games are in the news.* &lt;#ny&gt;

The Serious Games Summit D.C. is the only conference 100% dedicated to 
the emerging marketplace for games that are for more than play.

The Serious Games Summit D.C. gives game developers and program managers 
the opportunity to learn from successful serious games applications and 
forge links between the traditional videogame industry and public and 
private sectors; homeland security, state and local governments, 
military agencies, and educational institutions.

*Register online by September 15
* &lt;http://info.gamanetwork.com/cgi-bin4/DM/y/hjAt0FqZAJ0FdM0CkQd0A7&gt;* to 
save $200 on your Serious Games Summit D.C. pass. *

Serious Games Summit D.C.
October 18-19, 2004
Washington D.C.
*www.seriousgamessummit.com* 
&lt;http://info.gamanetwork.com/cgi-bin4/DM/y/hjAt0FqZAJ0FdM0ChHa0Ar&gt;


	**


    * *Washington Technology article - &quot;Let the Games Begin&quot;
      &lt;http://info.gamanetwork.com/cgi-bin4/DM/y/hjAt0FqZAJ0FdM0CkVi0AI&gt;*
    * *Comments from Ben Sawyer, Content Director for the Serious Games
      Summit D.C. &lt;#ben&gt;*
    * *Serious Games Summit D.C. Keynote & Featured Sessions* &lt;#keynote&gt;
    * *Opening Night Reception* &lt;#reception&gt;
    * *Early Registration discount savings of $200 end on September 15*
      &lt;#reg&gt;
    * *Hotel Reservations* &lt;#hotel&gt;






Below, Ben Sawyer, Serious Games Initiative Co-Director , comments on 
the market, growth, and networking opportunities available to developers 
at the Serious Games Summit D.C.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
&quot;If I told you a new publisher was starting up and they would publish 
twenty or more games a year with budgets between $100,000 and $5 million 
would you find that interesting?

If I told you most of the time they let you keep the IP you created for 
yourself would you find that interesting?

If I told you this new publisher was getting coverage in Newsweek, ABC 
World News Tonight, The New York Times, and G4 wouldn&#39;t that mean 
something?

What if I told you this upstart publisher was expected to be supplying 
potentially hundreds of new development contracts in the near future?

Well that publisher doesn&#39;t exist yet, but the &quot;Serious Games&quot; market 
does. Foundations, military, government, corporate, and educational 
customers are coming around to the idea that the games industry has 
technologies and talents they need to tap for future successes. These 
projects are not trivial and can in some cases rival the terms in the 
commercial game market.

Commercial developers and publishers big and small are finding new 
opportunities with non-traditional customers.

The Serious Games Summit D.C. is one of the best chances this year to 
get your foot in the door and learn more about how to find and develop 
successful non-entertainment game projects. We&#39;re bringing the experts, 
potential customers, and developers together for two days to help grow 
this exciting market. So take advantage of this opportunity and find out 
how you can leverage the benefits of working on games for non-industry 
customers toward greater succcess in the games industry overall. &quot;

Ben Sawyer
- /Content Director/, Serious Games Summit D.C.
- /Founder/, Digitalmill
-/ Co-Director/, Serious Games Initiative




*/Keynote Speakers/*:

*-A Life Developing Serious Games*
Jim Dunnigan

Jim Dunnigan is one of the first pioneers of serious games. In his 
keynote, Jim will share his vast experience and unique perspective on 
developing game-based simulations and models.

**-Real, Reel and Surreal: How Games Impact Perception
**Dr. Johnny L. Wilson

*/Recently added sessions:/

