                                    &lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;
 face=&quot;Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif&quot;&gt;Below, Ben Sawyer,
Serious Games Initiative Co-Director , comments on the market, growth,
and networking opportunities available to developers at the Serious
Games Summit D.C.&lt;/font&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
                                    &lt;hr&gt; &lt;font
 face=&quot;Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif&quot; size=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&quot;If I told you a
new publisher was starting up and they would publish twenty or more
games a year with budgets between $100,000 and $5 million would you
find that interesting? &lt;br&gt;
                                    &lt;br&gt;
If I told you most of the time they let you keep the IP you created for
yourself would you find that interesting? &lt;br&gt;
                                    &lt;br&gt;
If I told you this new publisher was getting coverage in Newsweek, ABC
World News Tonight, The New York Times, and G4 wouldn&#39;t that mean
something? &lt;br&gt;
                                    &lt;br&gt;
What if I told you this upstart publisher was expected to be supplying
potentially hundreds of new development contracts in the near future? &lt;br&gt;
                                    &lt;br&gt;
Well that publisher doesn&#39;t exist yet, but the &quot;Serious Games&quot; market
does. Foundations, military, government, corporate, and educational
customers are coming around to the idea that the games industry has
technologies and talents they need to tap for future successes. These
projects are not trivial and can in some cases rival the terms in the
commercial game market.&lt;br&gt;
                                    &lt;br&gt;
Commercial developers and publishers big and small are finding new
opportunities with non-traditional customers.&lt;br&gt;
                                    &lt;br&gt;
The Serious Games Summit D.C. is one of the best chances this year to
get your foot in the door and learn more about how to find and develop
successful non-entertainment game projects. We&#39;re bringing the experts,
potential customers, and developers together for two days to help grow
this exciting market. So take advantage of this opportunity and find
out how you can leverage the benefits of working on games for
non-industry customers toward greater succcess in the games industry
overall. &quot;&lt;/font&gt; &lt;font size=&quot;1&quot;
 face=&quot;Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;
                                    &lt;br&gt;
